article.headline: Chambers, Humphrey score 18 each
article.linkText: Georgia's fast start sinks Idaho in Hawaii
article.story:
HONOLULU (AP) -- A quick start was all Georgia needed to get past
Idaho.

Cori Chambers and Tasha Humphrey each scored 18 points Friday,
leading No. 3 Georgia to a 77-55 victory over the Vandals in the
opening round of the Rainbow Wahine Classic.

The Lady Bulldogs (3-0) made 10 of their first 16 shots and used
their size advantage and man-to-man defense to build a 22-7 lead
with 13 minutes left in the opening half.

"We showed pretty good poise getting the ball to the open man
and Tasha did a good job finishing early," Georgia coach Andy
Landers said.

Humphrey scored eight consecutive points during the early run.

"We cluttered up against her and on times we did, we didn't do
too bad with her," Idaho coach Mike Divilbiss said. "When we
didn't, she handled us. You got to make some adjustment. You can't
let her settle deep under the basket."

Idaho's Emily Faurholt, who averaged an NCAA-best 25.4 points
last season, missed her first eight shots and finished with 13
points on 4-for-21 shooting. Leilani Mitchell scored 18 points for
the Vandals (2-1), who don't have a player taller than 6-foot-1.

Georgia charged to a 43-19 lead at the break and led by as many
as 36 points early in the second half.

The Vandals went on a 12-2 run midway through the second half,
closing within 26 points, and got as close as 20.

Georgia faces the winner of the Texas Christian-California game
in Saturday's semifinals.
